values:
Here are my thoughts on Hama-con 4.  I had some expectations going it this being that it is year four that a lot of the lessons learned from previous years should have led to this year being pretty good because they are no longer a "new" con.  Lets face it year 1 a con is trying find it's way.  Year 2 you fix the failings of year 1.  Year 3 you do tweaks from the previous year.  Therefore year 4 it should be be smooth sailing ahead.  So my expectation were of a good con experience.  I decided to take my preschool age daughter with me because it is the only local anime con in our area.  I thought she would have a good time.  A friend of mine also brought along her 10 year old child as well.  We treated the day as Mother/Daughter Geek Outing. The overall feel was lackdasical.   Throughout the day everyone mulled around in a daze.  Pretty much everyone was having "hang out at the mall syndrome." I overhead several attendees say they were bored.  An was seen attendee riding up and down the elevator of the con hotel for several hours because she was bored and found that activity more entertaining the convention events.  This is not good thing.

Con site It was set up in the VBC south hall. They had so much space this year.  So much in fact it seems like they did not know what to do with it.  The layout is very awkward.  It seems the center piece of the con site was the "Brawl" area.  My guess was it was place prominently there to draw maximum attention from everywhere.  For me it felt as if this was very distracting from everything else going around.  In my opinion most attendees did not see to care about it.  The the left of the convention space were the hard walled rooms.  The dealers room as in the middle of the rooms.  This led to mess depending n the time of day because the line leading to the dealers room cut off the flow of foot traffic to the artists alley an other panel room. Either you cut through the line or walk around the Brawl area. Perhaps and room off line queue area would have been helpful.  The remainder of the convention space was in a large convention spaced portioned off with curtain partitions or rope.  You had to walk around the brawl space to get to the various attractions.

I do appreciate that there was a parents rest area.  It was a nice touch; however, putting it next to the gaming area was not a wise idea.  I'm sure that rest and relaxation area was all kinds of awesome with the sounds coming through the curtain partition from the gaming area.  Also Artist all was located along the back wall of the convention space.  It was portioned off with curtain partitions.  It had the literal feel of an alley due the way it was situated.  Truly awkward.  I do not mean this in a good way.  Random suggestion somewhat related:  give guardian/parent escorts their own unique badges.  I think this will be beneficial to staffers that they know that they are dealing with an attendees parent who is more than likely paying for that child's badge.  Also, giving them there own special designation is nice because you can tell if someone is rightfully sitting in that parent's lounge. Panels and Events As I mentioned I only attended on Saturday.  I went to three panels with my.  1 of the 3 was ran well.  It was the good folks over at Cosfluff. It was well organized.  The My Little Pony theme panel/event was quite haphazard and seemed to be poorly organized.  Please do not have a co-host for a panel that is not a fan of the series.  It is insulting to die hard fans (I am not so it did not offend me like it did some others I know).  The co panelist actually said it out loud.  Then finally there is the Pokemon panel.  I was peeved due to the fact that the panelist ignored a child that wanted to ask a question.  The child climbed up on to her chair and waved her arms around to get his attention.  Other members in the audience had to yell at him to make him acknowledge her.  It was not hard to notice her considering she was wearing a pastel wig.  She stood out. Pokemon is an all ages fandom.  To my knowledge I believe Hama-con still considers itself a family convention the panelist needs to be more child friendly and able to handle children better. A side rant:  if there is a parent panel please do not let it be ran by a non parent.  It is insulting to other parents.  Find subject matter experts on the subject.  I know for a fact there are parents and guardians on that staff. Staff and information Brief your staff well.  Especially the information people.  How can they give info without not know basic facts.  Also touching back on the lay out of the con space and large map at the info table would be useful.  There were accounts by other attendees that the staff was queried for information and failed to be able to get answers. I ended up missing cosplay pre judging because the information staff did not know the location of it.  Granted I purposely showed up close to the end of judging because I had a child entry for her personal comfort and convenience is why this occurred (and smart parenting).   Suggestions: add a dry erase board to write down info on changes to events.  Also clearly identify your staff with an official staff t-shirt.  Badges are nice and all but a t-shirt stands out more. Many cons do this.  Sure money is an issue as well but the importance of this outweighs the expense in my opinion. Forms, papers,  pamphlets and more.  Please post all of your forms on your website prior to the con.  This means registration forms, contest entry forms, maps, programs and such.  This is standard for most conventions.  Especially for cons past their 3rd year.  Being a newb con is not excuse for this.  During year 1 they did this so there is no excuse for this at all.  I found an electronic version of the program was published on a staffers twitter account and FB page.  Yay for the info but you know it would super awesome if you put it on official site as well.  It was paramount that program guide be posted to the website because this convention does not have a convention app.  This only makes it appear that the con staff is disorganized.  This is nothing new or foreign because during their first year most if not all of the aforementioned information was available on the website.  They need to to think of everything is being looked at by a non-geek Joe Schmo.  All information needs to be primarily posted on the official website.  That is your flag ship and your legitimate official face to the world.  Not your Twitter, Facebook or Tumblr accounts.  Social media should be used an enhancement to your website.  Not the number source for information.  As a parent if my child is going to ask me about a convention I will most definitely by default to a website first.  If you are not going to utilize your website properly why even have it at all.  As of this very moment at after 1PM on Sunday afternoon the con program guide was still not posted to the conventions website. In conclusion Hamacon 4 (Saturday) was just OK. There was an attempt to make it special by have the Brawl event all weekend but it just fell flat.  Most attendees seemed to treat it as one big hangout session because of the complaints of boredom.  Some in fact were mentioning forgoing Hama-con next year to attend other conventions around the same time of the year.  As any convention will say as they read their reviews and feedback will get defense by stating their events and staffing are built on the backs of volunteers who freely give their time.  Attendees know and appreciate this.  However, staff must also read every single review, every single tweet, message and such to gather all feedback positive and negative.  Take all of that information and fix what you can to be more successful in the following year.  I know in fact I have friends on the con staff were offended or irked at some of my Facebook posts in the final days leading up to the convention.  I like to think of it this way, you would rather hear it from a friend than a stranger first and fix the fail before the entire general public notices something amiss then complains. #Hamacon #Hamacon4 #Conventions

The is journal is a collection of all of my disjointed and random thoughts, rants, ideas and such. Please do not request to be added unless you are a close friend or a positive part of my day to day life that UPDATES THEIR JOURNAL.

After being faced with trust and privacy issues this is a friends only journal. I do not add people "just because." People who do not regularly undate their journals will not be added. I have come to learn that many people have visited my journal (and others) to troll and spy on the comments that other people leave. I found it rude and intrusive. Thus why I have close off my LJ from the prying eyes of the public.

If you are added it will be only a temporary trial basis. After that period has passed you will remain permanently friended or be removed.

I am fully aware of the lateness of this report therefore I apologize for the lateness of it. /swt2 Now that business is out of the way on to business.

Alabama Phoenix Festival was held May 25-27 2012 in Birmingham, AL. The genre for this event was sci fi/fantasy/comics. This is the first year for this convention so I was not sure what to expect. The convention venue was somewhat split between two venues. The bulk of the con was held at the Cahaba Grand Conference Center. Gaming was held at the Hilton Perimeter Park Hotel. Being a believer supporting my local con scene I decided to go check out to see what the con offered. Truth be told I was on the fence about attending the full weekend. I made decision to attend Saturday only and stay overnight. My bestie and I packed our bags and set out on overnight adventure.

The con atmosphere was very laid back. The main venue was very spacious. However, outside parking was very limited. However, additional parking was available at the con hotel and free shuttle was avaiable to transport them to the conference center. A little inconvenient but if you decided to tuck your flask of your favorite spirit then this was a very good option. Registration was very easy to find. It was front and center as you entered the con venue. The staff was very polite and helpful. I always like a nice con staff. Bonus points for APF. The actual con itself was one floor up which was accessible by either elevator and stair case. There was a large artist alley area; walk of fame hall and decent sized dealers/artist area as well. There were a variety of jewelry,t-shirts, comics and other hand crafts available all in line with the convention theme. It seemed they drew a lot of local artists and dealers in which is good. It's always a bonus to have your local artists support your local con to encourage future growth.

The con programming was plentiful and varied. Everything from drawing manga, costuming, Star Wars LARPing, Legos, and even a sit down with the Hero of Canton (Adam Baldwin) available to please every sort of geek fandom. Everyone got along together. This convention by far had to most approachable, chatty attendees I have ever had the pleasure of meeting. If you said something loud enough, others would join in your conversatgion. I had a wonderful conversation with a fellow kaiju fan a podcast about why Rebirth of Mosura movie series is great and the various themes that each movie represented. Another fun random conversation was about zombies. Costumers were everywhere and the variety of costume was varied as well. Doctor Who, Marvel comics, steampunk and Star Wars seemed to be the most popular genres. However, my personal favorite of the weekend was a Red Robin and Batgirl. We chatted at length and digressed into a 15 minute conversation about Young Justice. Call me bias but I am a DC fangirl LOL.

All in all I had a very good time. APF is what I call a relax-a-con: a very chill, laid back, low stress convention. I look forward to attending APF next year and cannot wait to see what they have to offer. For more information about APF please visit their website at: http://www.alabamaphoenixfestival.com/

Before I begin chronicling the events of this past weekend, I would like to point out that attended two conventions this weekend.  In addition to MTAC, Full Moon Tattoo and Horror convention happened in the same venue this weekend. As the name indicated it was a tattoo and horror themed convention.  MTAC had part of the 1st floor and 2 to 3 floors of the Nashville Convention Center.  Full Moon had part only part of the 1st floor.  It was rather a small con.  All I can say that was the most bizarre mix of fandoms ever.  However, my friend Blikku and I were one of the few that fell into that special cross-over category.  We are just weird like that.

The Renaissance Nashville Hotel was the main con hotel for this year's MTAC.  Hilton Nashville Downtown and Courtyard Nashville Downtown served as overflow hotels.  After looking at the general location of the overflow hotels in relation the con site it was comparable walking distance akin to walking from the Hilton to Hyatt at Dragon*Con, so not terribly too bad.  Also, since the convention was location smack in the heart of downtown Nashville, there was not want for local eateries convenience stores.  I spent part of Friday night and Saturday exploring some of the area around the convention. Thankfully there was beautiful weather to let me do all of this.  I like that a lot of things were close by.  The Renaissance Nashville Hotel in itself was nice.  The staff was amiable as well.  My check and check out went very smoothly.  No weird unexplained charges popped up on my bill.  So that was a welcome relief.  My friend and I arrived during the Friday morning and decided to do valet parking.  It was $29.50 (with tax) per day and worth every penny. If I had to leave I was guaranteed to have a parking spot upon return.  Also, it made checking in and out go 10 times easier.  If checked in early during the day, hotel guest received a room key with the MTAC Omega logo print on it.   It was pretty spiffy and a nice keepsake.  I was fortunate to have my room preference fulfilled and got a room on a low floor.  It was on the 6th to be exact.  I like to do this in the event there is elevator hell.  I learned the hard way at one of my first AWAs.  The room themselves had nice fluffy soft beds which were very nice.  Also flat screen TV, coffee maker and a converter box to hook up a gaming console.  Despite how nicely appoint the rooms are I think the hotel could stand to for some remodeling to update the decor.  Mainly the bathrooms needed a face lift.

This years MTAC was MTAC Omega, an end of the world apocalypse theme.  This was my first anime con in 2 1/2 years.  I decided to give it once last try before giving up on anime cons in general.  So I decided to go kill time in line up in the line queue to pick up con badge and anticipate what the weekend had in store for me.  That was around 8:45 am.  The line was already long and the registration did not open until 10 am.  Wow.  It continued to grow to the point where the preregistration line ended up running outside of the building and running along the sidewalk towards the hotel entrance.  The walk-in line was at respectable length.  Thankfully, MTAC staffers tweeted out that registration would open one hour early much to the relief of many Mtaku.  However, I must admit I did get a bit peeved.  To be specific, at the complaints of some of the attendees in line.  Some flat out refused to listen to Public Safety and go in the wrong line only to get infuriated when the realized the were in the wrong one and stomped off to the end of the appropriate line.  Another frequent complaint was the line wait.  I cannot remember for sure how long it took for me to get through the line.  It took approximately 45 to 60 minutes.  For me this is not big deal.  This was the average wait that I dealt with for AWA.  Past Dragon*Cons are even much longer.  So for me to hear a person whine about how long the wait was made me want to flip a table.  That was the first time I had the "get off my lawn syndrome."  Perhaps I'm getting too old for this mess.  Upon reaching the registration desk I presented my scanned receipt and picked up my badge and was on my way. That entire process was maybe 45 seconds.  WHY CAN'T ALL CONS USE BARCODES OR SIMILAR SYSTEMS?!  Looking up a person's name and printing off a custom badge with name takes entirely too long.  If the printer breaks, then that adds to the problems.

This year I decided to use the Guidebook app to have constant access to the MTAC schedule.  It was really great.  Of course it had the con schedule; detail list of dealers; maps of the convention and dealers room; to-do lists; user custom schedule and a few other tidbits.  Super useful, especially if you do not want to lug around a program guide all day long.  If there was a change of schedule, the staff would push updates to the app.  MUY USEFUL!  They get an A+ for innovative use of technology for this and pre-reg.

MTAC is an anime convention and one would expect to see traditional anime based costumes.  Adventure Time, Sailor Moon, Dragonball and My Little Pony FiM were the most numerous costumes of the weekend.  Also, several people were attired in elegant gothic Lolita clothing too.  But MTAC is famous for attendees wearing non-genre based costumes so Star Wars costumes, steampunk, comic book characters and other science fiction based costumes were seen as well.  Adding to the mix were the attendees from Full Moon con, lots of zombies, Goth garbed people walking around the shared convention space.  It kind of made me feel like I was at Dragon*Con due to the diversity of the costumes.  However, anime and video game characters were the majority.  My personal fan favorite was of a Shouma & Himari from Mawaru Penguindrum.

MTAC had very diverse programming with its events and panels.  They ranged from things in the chibi track all the way to over 18 programming.  Lots of general anime fan panels, cosplay panels, gaming tourneys were scheduled.  Samplings of the main events were Symphonic Anime Orchestra concerts, End of the World Rave, Blitzball matches and Kaiju vs. Pro Wrestling.  Overall the MTAC staff was very helpful and cordial.  If you had a problem or question via twitter, Facebook (thanks Yukarikiss <3) or to someone in person they were more that willing to take care of you. I think my only real gripe was the wait for Risqué Cosplay.  That was the one event that was at the top of my to-do list.  I got in line 45 minutes prior to the event because I knew was popular and would be hard to get seats for.  Then I waited another hour.  The total wait was 1 hour 45 minutes.  The event ended up starting an hour late.  Irony, whatever issue was going on was resolved five minutes after my friends and I got out of line. Also, a karaoke event I wanted to attend was cancelled as well.  The dealers’ room was gargantuan in comparison to what was seen in past years.  I was very excited to see it expanded so much.  A good variety of dealers were there.  So pretty much majority of most otaku shopping needs could be filled in one spot.

As mentioned before, Full Moon shared the convention center with MTAC.  A friend and I purchased a cross over day pass for $5.  Also, MTAC was selling the reverse version of the same pass to attendees at Full Moon.  I thought that was kind of neat.  The atmosphere at Full Moon was laid back, slacker mode, super chill and walk around with a drink in your hand.  "Hakuna matata" was the perfect description for this crowd.  If a panel got cancelled, no big deal because everyone was ok with it.  They all rolled with it.  This was the polar opposite from the high energy hyper anime crowd.  Most of the attendees were adults with the exception of a handful of children there with their parents. The main portion of the convention was housed in the dealers’ room.  3/4 of it was set aside for various tattoo artists, movie vendors, gaming shops and clothing dealers.  Remaining quarter of the space was their walk of fame for the convention's guests.  Very similar to what you would see a Dragon*Con as well.  Chiller Brothers, Kristen Bauer had a table.  I saw an actress from I Spit on Your Grave too.  However, the pièce de résistance for me was Tony Todd and Norman Reedus.  Fans of classic horror movies will recognize Tony Todd from Candyman.  He also has starred in a Final Destination movie and I also remember him from Stargate SG-1.  My inner fan girl flailed.  In so much I slipped and address my friend by a nickname I have for her which I did not intend and embarrassed myself.  It was too funny now that I think back on it.  Tony was very nice and laid bad he asked us how we like the con and even asked us about MTAC.  He was a genuinely nice guy.  A day later my friend and I paid to get pictures with Norman Reedus.  For those of you living under a rock, Norman was in The Boondock Saints as Murphy McManus.  Also, more recently as Daryl on AMCs The Walking Dead.  I am an uber fan for both and was all kinds of happy to find out that he was at Full Moon.  As I type this I am still on a high from my fan girl euphoria from meeting him.  Again way super cool and really nice.  I got a hug and a booty bump from him.  I thought things couldn't get any better after meeting Tony Todd.  I was wrong. My fan girl levels are OVER 9000! It made my entire weekend.  I saw other women leaving the room where photos were being taken at as I stood in line.  Many exited blushing, squealing or fanning themselves.  I completely understood why after I had my encounter.  Also, meeting guests at this event was far easier, cheaper and less time consuming than at Dragon*Con.  Totally worth the $5 pass.

All in all this past weekend was a good experience.  Despite some hiccups, MTAC was fun. Full Moon was as equally fun in a different way.  Both events had variety events that were unique to their genres.  And I applaud them for hosting an event that incorporated pro wrestling/kaiju wrestling cross over as well.  I thought that was a clever idea.  I truly hope that next year both cons end up on the same dates and work out the same kind of deal.  Lets go over my list of dislikes.   I was disappointed that my favorite events were cancelled or started very late.  Also, I felt Public Safety was not vigilant enough.  The staffers dressed like 30s/40s gangsters acted like what I expect of MTAC Public Safety: dependable, sticklers to the rules and reasonably aggressive when required.  However, the ones dressed in the black t-shirts lacked the authoritative attitude I am so used to and at times failed to clear the crowd path ways, or flat out ignored horseplay.  The horseplay made me have a case of “get off my lawn complex” again.  After considering everything I give my overall experience a B+.  I would go back to MTAC again next year.

Oh yeah I'm feeling the stress. So lets recap on what left top do

Wig:
Complete ponytail (almost done)
Work on gigantic hair bow

Head dress (not as bad as it sounds):
Glue on orbs
Paint
Glue on gem
Glue on hat pins
Add Earrings
Add hair jewelry falls
Bead

Garment work:
Cut & sew collar


So I know it sounds like a shit crap ton. But the clothing is done minus the collar. I actually wore it all together and I'm pleased with the overall fit. A little big in the bodice (cause the last fitting was done during shark week). But a really good solid piece. The collar really is easy. But patterning it is the hard part. Once I get that one last peak figured out I will do the final pattern tonight and cut/sew. Hoping to have it out of the way be tomorrow night. The wig I hope to have the pony tail done tonight and part of the hair bow started.

Ok I have my game plan down. Mostly prop/wig work for the remainder of the week. Probaly wont finish 100% until Friday at the con because I need the helping hooves of  to help me out.

OMG OMG OMG OMG!  My Arda wigs have not arrived yet.  I was stuck in this situation because the wigs I originally needed are on back order till April.  So I changed my costume 30 days out.  AND ordered my wigs 30 days out.  But we all saw how that turned out. Yeah a hot mess.  So not I'm in a tissy.  

Speaking of tissy and spazz fits... more along spazz I am out of fabric.  BRB (goes to order fabric)

6:55am  Ok fabric ordered.  It should be here by Thursday.  I live 1 state away from Fabric.com warehouse so no worries.  But um yea like I completely cut the shirt fabric all jank and had to recut.  Plus I ordered short because the reference pic I had was WRONG WRONG WRONG.  After watching the anime ep like 5 times did I confirm there is an over skirt so um yeah.. FREAK THE FUCK OUT AND SPAZZ SOME MORE!!! *face palm*  *twitch*

But yeah the suck.  Upside I have the bodice sew and lined.  Boned too.  What a relief.  I will bias it and add the zipper tonight.  I need to add the collar soon but ugh time is running short.  @_@

This past week has been ups and down. Good. Arda's epic wig sale concluded and I got what I need. However, everyone and their cousin placed an order as well. This overwhelmed their very inefficient shopping cart system. End result: taking forever and a day to get will shipped. Think as of this weekend they are up to order # 9602. Which is good because my main order is like 92xx or something like that. So I will ship this week. Therefore will have the time required to style the wig. I probably will not see it until next week which is ok. I need to focus on the costume itself.

I got the charmeuse for the upper part of the skirt cut out this weekend. It's darted and pressed. I will go ahead and knock out the lower skirt tonight while I do laundry. I have a Thai silk version of the skirt already completed so it will serve as the lining. It's soft and flowy but has more structure and weight than the charmeuse. Oh and this satin charmeuse is so divine! Its like flowing water on the skin. I want to roll around in it. <3

Down sound. It's very difficult to work with and take a slow patient hand. I'm fine with that. But I do realize it'll make finishing this a bit more tedious.

It seems there is never enough time but I need to put my head down and persevere.  Well wig avail issues cropped up so in the 11th hour I had to post pone my costume and start on a new one.  Yeah... have NOTHING on hand for it.  So I hit up Arda and ordered what I needed. Actually got a 3rd one today @_@. 

As of now I've spent a crap ton of time rewatching 3 episodes constantly to figure out how the costume looks.  True to form the hair color varies.  The character's outfit changes.  Give me a break already.  Like seriously.  I figured out how to work out the wig.  Yay.  Also, I have prepared stencil patterns for the props.  Just waiting on that wonderflex to arrive tomorrow.

The costume itself.  I started the lining for it yesterday since I spent all of last week in stencil hell.  I have one piece of the lining done.    One more to go.  Technically done but I wanted to double line it so that I can run a some light boning into it.  I will know that out tonight because I want it done before the fabric arrives... also tomorrow.  Lots to do. Must stay positive and make it work.  Thank goodness I'm off Wednesday so I can have some sweatshop time.

Measure once cut twice as they say in the sewing world.  Nuh uh.  For me it's measure thrice, cut twice because in costuming land we all no there are no real exact patterns in existance for most of our creations. Therefore its all a trial by fire type of existance we lead.  I will tell you I am now going to have to cut thrice.  Well I did some shirring last night.  The first run I was less than pleased.  I did it with elastic thread.  I didn't like it because the WHITE elastic bobbin thread pulling through to the right side of the fabric was less than attractive.  My fabric isn't white so it looked horrid IMO.

Trial two.  MUCH BETTER!  I was very pleased with the result.  So I go to steam and set the puffing of the shirring to shrink it.  Afterwards I lay it over the area to place it into the garment and um about 5 inches short.  FUUUUUUUU!  Table flip.  So tonight I will be doing a "third time is a charm" while I'm watching Being Human.

Upside the skirt is assembled.  Again there were in progress revisions.  The tiers I measured ended up being too long.  End result: carefully seam ripping the entire thing apart.  So that was what, 20 minutes to sew and 4 hours to seam rip.  This is casa satin I'm dealing with so slow and patient pace was used.  It's now all back together after being shortened.  I will sew up the back seam after I do all the applique work along the hemline.    Oh yeah I had to seam rip the back of the blouse apart as well.  Just 2 panels to be able to add in that shirring.

Tonight's to-do list:  do that damn shirring AGAIN!  Sew shirring into blouse.  Despite my angst and loathing I am having fun merging two character designs into one.  I did decide to enter it for MTAC but in really I want to use that con as a proving ground to test it out and tweak it before Dragon*Con (not competing there).  I just can imagine all of the Peaches I will stalk and play kill/battle in this costume.  Yeah I'm twisted much.  Ok enough for now.  On to doing my real job.

HAPPY MARCH! (that was random)

Well it is quite evident that I've been away from the form or social networking for a while with the random update here and there because I've be tediously working away at problem solving since say November.  Yes kiddies.  Sometimes you have to start MONTHS in advance to work on mock ups and inventing neccessary techniques before you can work on a project.  My current costume that I love and loathe has put me in a very frustrating place.  Last month I posted a video of part of that problem solving as well.  But that was only part of it because I learned Brother sewing machines do not like elastic thread in the bobbin.  ANGST!   But I have that all sorted out now. 

Yet still a crucial part of this costume building process eluded me more even longer until I finally sorted it out 2 weeks out on accident.  I was SO close to solving this that I wanted to kick myself.  Wish I had this break through much sooner seeing that MTAC is what?  36 days away... 5 weeks.
FIVE WEEKS UNTIL MTAC

*Kermit flail freak out mode*

Last night I did manage to get to the skirt construction.  I have sewn and pressed seams on nine pieces of fabric that measure 18 inches height by 60 in width.  So after some math that's say 15 yards of fabric because I joined all of the pieces together.  Lets not even talk about cutting all of that to ensure it was the EXACT same measurement everytime.  Or the burning sensation I have in my left thumb because a managed to inadvertantly nick my left thumb and left ring finger during the process.  BTDubs:  Olfa rotary cutting blades are super sharp.  Tonight I shall continue messing with the by hemming ALL OF THAT SHIT!  @_@  I two sections are done.  Seven to go.  *weak yay*  the other side of the fabric I'm gonna leave raw because I have already pinked it. So no unraveling.  Rotary cutter with a pinked blade FTW (even if it is super crazy sharp blood thirsty).    Oh the reason I'm pre-hemming it is because it will be a finished hemline. Granted lace will cover it.  But I'm just OCD like that.  =)   When it's all said and done I will move on to lightly gathering the pinked side of the fabric. 

Yeah alot of work to do.   I really need to go to my google calendar and set up my task list so I can manage my work effectively.

If you are still trying to book a room at a con hotel I have pleasant news. The Westin JUST added rooms to their room block. Hop on it now while you can. Room rate is $185.00. They will charge a one night deposit of $214.60 (tax included) at the time of reservation.

And knowing is half the battle. And smart ass remarks of "I booked at the Hilton during D*Con 2011" and akin are not welcome. Most people could care less about that hotel in terms of prime locale.
Posted via LiveJournal app for Android.
